E-B-S: block storage for E-C-2.

An E-B-S volume is a network-attached block device that an E-C-2 instance sees as a local disk. Because it's on the network rather than inside the host, three properties follow. It can detach from one instance and reattach to another, within the same availability zone. It persists independently of the instance, surviving stop and terminate, unless the Delete-on-Termination flag is set; that's on by default for the root volume and off for additional volumes. And it pays a tiny network-latency tax, which is negligible except for the most latency-sensitive work. E-B-S is availability-zone-scoped: a volume only attaches to instances in its own zone, and crossing zones or regions goes through a snapshot. Most volumes attach to one instance at a time; Multi-Attach, on io1 and io2 only, allows up to sixteen.

Volume types split into S-S-D and H-D-D. G-P-3 is the default for almost everything: three thousand I-O-P-S and a hundred twenty-five megabytes per second baseline regardless of size, with I-O-P-S and throughput dialled independently, and about twenty percent cheaper than g-p-2, which ties I-O-P-S to size at three per gigabyte. Io2 and io2 Block Express are provisioned-I-O-P-S S-S-D for I-O-intensive and the very largest databases, up to two hundred fifty-six thousand I-O-P-S. S-T-1, a throughput H-D-D, suits sequential big-data and logs; s-c-1, a cold H-D-D, suits rarely-accessed bulk; and both are not bootable.

The short decision: g-p-3 unless you have a reason. Io2 for demanding databases, and s-t-1 or s-c-1 for sequential or cold bulk.
